<h1 id="step-5">Step 5</h1>

<h2 id="enabling-cloudfront">Enabling CloudFront</h2>

<p>Now itâ€™s time to set up CloudFront for your website. Essentially, CloudFront distributes your site across AWS edge locations, providing better performance to the end-user.</p>

<p>To get started with setting this up, head into the CloudFront service and click on â€˜Create Distributionâ€™.</p>

<p>Under â€˜Origin Domain Nameâ€™, enter the url you copied earlier, minus the protocol. For example, the link generated for my bucket is http://blog.thanesh.io.s3-website-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com. Therefore, the value Iâ€™ll enter into this field is blog.thanesh.io.s3-website-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com.</p>

<p>It is important you do not select from one of the options given in the drop down, otherwise, this will not work. Youâ€™ll have to copy and paste the url as Iâ€™ve described above.</p>

<p><img src="../images/jekyll_on_AWS/create-distribution.png" alt="create-distribution" /></p>

<p>You can keep most of the settings as their default. However, under â€˜Alternate Domain Namesâ€™, youâ€™ll want to enter your registered domain name. Next, scroll to the bottom and hit â€œCreate Distributionâ€™. This could take about 10-15 minutes to be deployed.</p>

<h1 id="step-6">Step 6</h1>

<h2 id="linking-up-your-domain">Linking up your Domain</h2>

<p>By this stage, you should have your website deployed and set up with CloudFront. In this final part, weâ€™ll work through setting up your domain so that people know how to access your site.</p>

<p>Firstly, head into Route53, click on â€˜Hosted Zonesâ€™ from the left hand column and then create a hosted zone by entering your chosen domain.</p>

<p>Once youâ€™ve created this, you should see a NS record appear. Copy each of the values from this field and enter it into your domain provider. Essentially, this will allow Route53 to handle the configuration of the domain.</p>

<p>Next, while in your hosted zone, click on â€˜Create Recordâ€™. Here we want to connect our domain with our CloudFront distribution we created earlier. Make sure it is an â€˜A recordâ€™ and click on the â€˜Aliasâ€™ switch in the right hand corner. In the dropdown that appears, select â€˜Alias to CloudFront distributionâ€™ which prefills the region to â€˜US East (N. Virginia). Click into the search box and select the CloudFront distribution we made from before.</p>

<p><img src="../images/jekyll_on_AWS/record.png" alt="record" /></p>

<p>Hit â€˜Create Recordâ€™ and youâ€™re all set! Be patient as it may take a couple of hours to set in.</p>

<h1 id="step-7">Step 7</h1>

<h2 id="redirection-for-www-and-ssl">Redirection for WWW and SSL</h2>

<p>At this point your site should be up and live. However, if you type in www. before your domain, it will produce an error.</p>

<p>Fixing this is similar to the process weâ€™ve just done, with a few minor adjustments. Youâ€™ll want to go back and follow the steps from before but when creating another bucket, youâ€™ll want to prepend it with â€˜wwwâ€™ and under â€˜Static Website Hostingâ€™, choose the â€˜Redirectâ€™ option - setting it your domain. In this bucket, you donâ€™t have to add any files as it is purely for redirection.</p>

<p>After this, setup another CloudFront distribution linking to your â€˜wwwâ€™ bucket. Add another â€˜A recordâ€™ in your hosted zone and set the Alias Target to your new CloudFront url.</p>

<p>As a final note, if you want to setup SSL, go back into the CloudFront distributions you created earlier and find the SSL Certificate option. Under here, choose the â€˜Custom SSL Certificateâ€™ option and click on â€˜Request or Import a Certificate with ACMâ€™. This is fairly straightforward, especially if your domain is already setup in Route53.</p>

